25|$|Kali puja: This {{festival is}} {{dedicated}} to the Hindu Goddess Kali and is celebrated on <b>the</b> <b>new</b> <b>moon</b> day of the Hindu month of Kartik. It coincides with the pan-Indian festival of Diwali amidst the bursting of firecrackers.|$|E
25|$|However, about 5 or 6 lunations later <b>the</b> <b>new</b> <b>moon</b> {{will fall}} {{close to the}} {{opposite}} node. In that time (half an eclipse year) the Sun will have moved to the opposite node too, so the circumstances will again be suitable for one or more eclipses.|$|E
50|$|<b>The</b> ecclesiastical <b>new</b> <b>moon</b> which {{falls on}} or next after March 8 is of special importance, {{since it is}} <b>the</b> paschal <b>new</b> <b>moon</b> that begins <b>the</b> paschal lunar month (see table). The fourteenth day of the same lunar month {{is the first of}} the {{calendar}} year to occur on or next after March 21. This fourteenth day was called the paschal full moon by medieval computists. Easter is the following Sunday.|$|R
50|$|A {{continuing}} lunisolar calendar {{is in the}} Hebrew calendar. Evidence of this {{is noted}} in the dates of Passover and Easter in Judaism and Christianity, respectively. The date of the Jewish Rosh Hashana and Sukkot festivals along with all other Jewish holidays are dependent on the dates of <b>the</b> <b>new</b> <b>moons.</b>|$|R
